In mathematical [[finite group|finite]] [[group theory]], the '''Gorenstein–Harada theorem''', proved by {{harvs|txt|last=Gorenstein|author1-link=Daniel Gorenstein|last2=Harada|author2-link=Koichiro Harada|year1=1973|year2=1974}} in a 464 page paper,<ref>[https://medium.com/@camirosso/abc-conjecture-the-enormity-of-math-91c773f43ba3 "Abc conjecture — The Enormity of Math"]. ''Medium'', Cami Rosso, Feb 23, 2017</ref> classifies the simple finite groups of sectional 2-rank at most 4. It is part of the [[classification of finite simple groups]].<ref name="Oliver2016">{{cite book|author=Bob Oliver|title=Reduced Fusion Systems over 2-Groups of Sectional Rank at Most 4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zDl4CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA3|date=25 January 2016|publisher=American Mathematical Soc.|isbn=978-1-4704-1548-8|pages=1, 3}}</ref>

Finite simple groups of section 2 that rank at least 5, have Sylow 2-subgroups with a self-centralizing [[normal subgroup]] of rank at least 3, which implies that they have to be of either [[component type]] or of [[characteristic 2 type]]. Therefore, the Gorenstein–Harada theorem splits the problem of classifying finite simple groups into these two sub-cases.

