In [[mathematics]], the '''Gorenstein–Walter theorem''', proved by {{harvs|txt|last=Gorenstein|last2=Walter|year1=1965a|year2=1965b| year3=1965c}}, states that if a [[finite group]] ''G'' has a [[dihedral group|dihedral]] Sylow 2-subgroup, and ''O''(''G'') is the maximal [[normal subgroup]] of odd [[order (group theory)|order]], then ''G''/''O''(''G'') is isomorphic to a 2-group, or the [[alternating group]] ''A''<sub>7</sub>, or a subgroup of PΓL<sub>2</sub>(''q'') containing PSL<sub>2</sub>(''q'') for ''q'' an odd prime power. Note that A<sub>5</sub> ≈ PSL<sub>2</sub>(4) ≈ PSL<sub>2</sub>(5) and A<sub>6</sub> ≈ PSL<sub>2</sub>(9).


