In mathematical [[finite group theory]], the '''Thompson transitivity theorem''' gives conditions under which the [[Centralizer and normalizer|centralizer]] of an [[abelian subgroup]] ''A'' acts [[transitively]] on certain subgroups normalized by ''A''. It originated in the proof of the [[Feit–Thompson theorem|odd order theorem]] by {{harvs|txt|last=Feit|last2=Thompson|author2-link=John G. Thompson|year=1963}}, where it was used to prove the [[Thompson uniqueness theorem]].

==Statement==
Suppose that ''G'' is a finite group and ''p'' a [[prime]] such that all [[P-local subgroup|''p''-local subgroups]] are [[p-constrained|''p''-constrained]]. If ''A'' is a self-centralizing normal abelian subgroup of a ''p''-Sylow subgroup such that ''A'' has rank at least 3, then the centralizer C<sub>''G''</sub>(''A'') act transitively on the maximal ''A''-invariant ''q'' subgroups of ''G'' for any prime&nbsp;''q''&nbsp;≠&nbsp;''p''.

